1. Payroll functionality & deductions
    PayrollRecord (in model/PayrollRecord.java):
    Added client (department/client for the payment).
    Pay period fields: payPeriodStart, payPeriodEnd for prorated deductions.
    Deductions aligned with Philippine rules:
    SSS: Tiered by monthly salary credit (~4.5% of MSC, capped).
    PhilHealth: 4% of basic salary with monthly floor Php 200 and ceiling Php 5,000.
    Pag-IBIG: 1% if monthly ≤ Php 1,500, otherwise 2%, with cap.
    Withholding tax: TRAIN graduated rates (0% up to 250k, then 20%, 25%, 30%, 32%, 35%).
    All amounts rounded to 2 decimal places.
2. Receipts
    ReceiptGenerator (in util/ReceiptGenerator.java):
    Writes one HTML receipt per employee (employee ID, name, client, hours, rate, gross, each deduction, total deductions, net pay, pay period).
    Optional company name and pay period end.
    Receipts are printable and can be opened in a browser.
3. Client handling
    CSV: Optional 5th column client; existing 4-column CSVs still work.
    Table: New Client column; totals and receipts include client where provided.
    Export: Exported CSV includes a Client column.
4. Payroll generator
    Generate Receipts: Choose a folder; one HTML receipt per employee is generated.
    Export Payroll CSV: Save full payroll (including client and all deductions) to CSV.
    Company name: Text field used as company name on receipts.
    Summary: Live totals for employee count, total gross, total deductions, total net.
5. GUI and long names
    Name column: minWidth="140", prefWidth="180".
    Client column: minWidth="120", prefWidth="140".
    Tooltips on Name, Client, and Employee ID so the full value is visible on hover when truncated.
    Resize policy: CONSTRAINED_RESIZE_POLICY_FLEX_LAST_COLUMN so the table uses width and the last column flexes.
    Layout: Buttons in an HBox, summary label, padding; table has VBox.vgrow="ALWAYS" and a minimum height.
6. CSV and sample data
    CSVReader: Supports quoted fields with commas; optional client column.
    testme.csv: Updated with a client column and a third employee with a long name to show tooltips and column width.

1. Professor’s CSV structure (from allreporttest.csv)
Line 1: Title: Attendance summary,... (used only for format detection).
Line 2: Date range: Date,2025-01-26 ~ 2025-02-10 (pay period).
Line 3: Main header: ID, Name, Dept., Working hours, ....
Line 4: Sub-header: ,,, Standard, Actual, ... (skipped).
Line 5+: Data rows. Important columns by index:
0 = ID, 1 = Name, 2 = Dept., 3 = Working hours (Standard) in HH:MM (e.g. 128:00).
There is no hourly rate in this format; gross is computed as hours × default hourly rate.
2. What was changed
New: ParseUtils.java
parseDouble(s, defaultValue) – safe parsing for numbers; returns default on null/blank/invalid (no crash).
parseHoursMinutesToDecimalHours(timeStr) – parses "HH:MM" (e.g. 128:00, 1:30) to decimal hours.
parseDate(s) – parses "yyyy-MM-dd" to LocalDate; returns null on failure.
parseDateRange(s) – parses strings like "2025-01-26 ~ 2025-02-10" into start/end dates.
All of this keeps parsing safe and avoids crashes on bad or missing data.
Updated: CSVReader.java
Format detection: Reads the first line and the header line. If the first line contains "Attendance summary" and the header contains "ID" and ("Dept." or "Working hours" or "Name"), the file is treated as the professor’s attendance report. Otherwise it is treated as the legacy format.
Professor’s format:
Skips lines 0–3 (title, date, two header rows).
Data from line 4 onward: ID (col 0), Name (col 1), Dept. (col 2) → mapped to Client, Working hours (col 3) as HH:MM → converted to decimal hours.
Pay period taken from line 2 (Date, start ~ end).
Hourly rate: not in the file; uses default (see below).
Legacy format: Unchanged: first line = header, then rows with employeeId, name, hoursWorked, hourlyRate [, client]. Uses your existing parsing and parseDouble for safe numeric parsing.
Missing/extra columns: Uses column indices only. Missing columns yield empty string or 0.0 via safeTrim and ParseUtils.parseDouble; extra columns are ignored.
API:
readCSV(path) – auto-detect format; for attendance format uses DEFAULT_HOURLY_RATE (100.0).
readCSV(path, defaultHourlyRate) – same, but uses the given rate for attendance format when defaultHourlyRate != null.
Updated: PayrollController.java
Injects defaultRateField (new text field).
loadCSV() reads the default-rate field: if it’s a non‑negative number, passes it as the second argument to CSVReader.readCSV(path, rate); otherwise passes null so the reader uses DEFAULT_HOURLY_RATE for attendance files.
Uses ParseUtils.parseDouble so invalid input in the rate field doesn’t crash.
Updated: payroll-view.fxml
Added “Default hourly rate (attendance report):” and a text field (defaultRateField) so the user can set the rate used when loading the professor’s CSV. If left empty or invalid, 100.0 is used.
Unchanged (as required)
PayrollRecord.java – no change; deduction logic and net pay stay the same.
ReceiptGenerator.java – unchanged; still one receipt per employee.
PayrollExport.java – unchanged; export and payroll generation unchanged.
Deduction calculations, net pay, payroll generation, and per‑employee receipts are preserved.
3. Assumptions about the professor’s CSV
Working hours are in column index 3 (first “Working hours” column = Standard). Format is hours:minutes (e.g. 128:00, 00:00). Any other columns (Actual, Late, Early, Overtime, etc.) are not used for gross pay in this implementation.
No hourly rate in the file → gross = hours × default hourly rate (user can set in “Default hourly rate (attendance report)” or fallback 100.0).
Pay period is only taken from line 2, second column, in the form start ~ end (or similar with ~). Used for deduction proration and receipts.
Department is column index 2 and is mapped to Client in the app (table and receipts).
Data rows are from line 5 (0-based index 4) onward. Rows with both ID and Name empty are skipped. Empty lines are skipped.
Format detection is based on first line containing “Attendance summary” and the header line containing “ID” and one of “Dept” / “Working hours” / “Name”. Any other structure is treated as legacy format.
4. How to run
Run the app (e.g. mvn javafx:run).
(Optional) Enter a value in “Default hourly rate (attendance report)” (e.g. 100). If you leave it blank, 100.0 is used for professor’s files.
Click “Load Payroll CSV” and choose allreporttest.csv (or any professor-format or legacy CSV).
Table will show ID, Name, Dept. as Client, hours (from HH:MM), rate (default for professor’s format), gross, deductions, net. Generate receipts and export payroll as before.

